Here's the opening — about 650 words. Two sections:

"Previously, on..." — Recaps the four gates, the users-vs-gatekeepers distinction, and Autonomy Debt without re-explaining them from scratch. Just enough that someone who read Part 1 three weeks ago gets re-oriented, and someone who didn't can follow along.

"Now We Remove the Gates" — Pivots to Part 2's domain (crypto trading) with a rationale for why the domain shift matters architecturally, introduces Alignment Risk as the counterweight to Autonomy Debt, and sets up the escalation structure.

Stylistically I matched: emoji h2 headers, bold-on-first-use for defined terms, second-person address, blockquote for the conceptual punch, and the same pattern of "observation → punchline → but seriously here's why it matters." The 3 AM candlestick line and the lawyer line are earning their keep the same way the suggestion-box joke did in Part 1.

